# CHAPTER III.

Dh*ri*tarâsh*t*ra said:

Who possesses this taciturnity <span id="fr_714"></span>[5](#fn_709.md),
and which of the two <span id="fr_715"></span>[6](#fn_710.md) is
taciturnity? Describe, O learned person! the condition of taciturnity
here. Does a learned man reach taciturnity <span
id="fr_716"></span>[7](#fn_711.md) by taciturnity? And how, O sage! do they
practise taciturnity in this world

<span id="page_163">p. 163</span>

Sanatsu*g*âta said:

Since the Vedas, together with the mind <span
id="fr_717"></span>[1](#fn_712), fail to attain to him, hence (is he.md)
taciturnity <span id="fr_718"></span>[2](#fn_713.md)--he about whom the
words of the Vedas were uttered <span id="fr_719"></span>[3](#fn_714.md),
and who, O king! shines forth as consubstantial <span
id="fr_720"></span>[4](#fn_715.md) with them.

Dh*ri*tarâsh*t*ra said:

Does <span id="fr_721"></span>[5](#fn_716.md) the twice-born person who
studies the *Rik* and the Ya*g*us texts, and the Sâma-veda, committing
sinful (acts), become tainted, or does he not become tainted?

Sanatsu*g*âta said

Not the Sâman texts, nor yet the *Rik* Texts, nor the Ya*g*us
texts <span id="fr_722"></span>[6](#fn_717.md) save him, O acute sir! from
sinful

<span id="page_164">p. 164</span>

action. I do not tell you an untruth. The *Kh*andas do not save a sinful
deceitful <span id="fr_723"></span>[1](#fn_718.md) man who behaves
deceitfully <span id="fr_724"></span>[2](#fn_719.md). At the time of the
termination (of his life), the *Kh*andas abandon <span
id="fr_725"></span>[3](#fn_720.md) him, as birds who have got wings
(abandon their) nest.

Dh*ri*tarâsh*t*ra said

If, O acute sir! the Vedas are not able to save one who understands the
Vedas, then whence is this eternal talk <span
id="fr_726"></span>[4](#fn_721.md) of the Brâhma*n*as?

Sanatsu*g*âta said:

O you of great glory! this universe becomes manifest through his special
forms--names <span id="fr_727"></span>[5](#fn_722.md) and the rest. The
Vedas proclaim (his form) after describing (it) well <span
id="fr_728"></span>[6](#fn_723.md), and (they <span
id="fr_729"></span>[7](#fn_724) also.md) state his difference from the
universe. For that <span id="fr_730"></span>[8](#fn_725.md) are this
penance and sacrifice prescribed. By these a learned man acquires merit,
and afterwards destroying sin by merit <span
id="fr_731"></span>[9](#fn_726.md), he has his self illuminated by
knowledge. By knowledge the learned man attains

<span id="page_165">p. 165</span>

the self <span id="fr_732"></span>[1](#fn_727.md). But, on the other hand,
one who wishes for the fruit--heaven <span
id="fr_733"></span>[2](#fn_728.md)--takes with him <span
id="fr_734"></span>[3](#fn_729) all that he has done in this (world.md),
enjoys it in the next, and then returns to the path <span
id="fr_735"></span>[4](#fn_730) (of this world.md). Penance is performed in
this world; the fruit is enjoyed elsewhere. But the penance of
Brâhma*n*as is further developed <span id="fr_736"></span>[5](#fn_731.md);
that of others remains only as much (as when first performed).

Dh*ri*tarâsh*t*ra said:

How does the pure penance become developed and well developed <span
id="fr_737"></span>[6](#fn_732)? O Sanatsu*g*âta! tell (me..md) how I
should understand that, O Lord!

Sanatsu*g*âta said:

This penance, free from sin <span id="fr_738"></span>[7](#fn_733.md), is
called pure <span id="fr_739"></span>[8](#fn_734.md); and this pure penance
becomes developed and well developed, not otherwise <span
id="fr_740"></span>[9](#fn_735.md). All this <span
id="fr_741"></span>[10](#fn_736.md), O Kshatriya!

<span id="page_166">p. 166</span>

has for its root that penance about which you question me. By
penance <span id="fr_742"></span>[1](#fn_737.md), those conversant with the
Vedas attained immortality, after departing from this world.

Dh*ri*tarâsh*t*ra said.

1 have heard about penance free from sin, O Sanatsu*g*âta! Tell me what
is the sin (connected) with penance, so that I may understand the
eternal mystery <span id="fr_743"></span>[2](#fn_738.md).

Sanatsu*g*âta said:

The twelve beginning with wrath, and likewise the seven cruelties, are
the defects (connected) with it; and there are (stated) in the Sâstras
twelve merits (connected) with it, beginning with knowledge, which are
known to the twice-born, and may be developed. Wrath, desire <span
id="fr_744"></span>[3](#fn_739.md), avarice, delusion <span
id="fr_745"></span>[4](#fn_740.md), craving <span
id="fr_746"></span>[5](#fn_741.md), mercilessness, censoriousness, vanity,
grief <span id="fr_747"></span>[6](#fn_742.md), attachment <span
id="fr_748"></span>[7](#fn_743.md), envy <span
id="fr_749"></span>[8](#fn_744.md), reviling others--these twelve should
always be avoided by a man of high

<span id="page_167">p. 167</span>

qualifications <span id="fr_750"></span>[1](#fn_745.md). These, O king of
kings! attend each and every man, wishing to find some opening <span
id="fr_751"></span>[2](#fn_746), as a hunter (watches.md) animals.
\[Boastful, lustful, haughty, irascible, unsteady <span
id="fr_752"></span>[3](#fn_747.md), one who does not protect (those
dependent <span id="fr_753"></span>[4](#fn_748) on him.md), these six
sinful acts are performed by sinful men who are not afraid (even) in the
midst of great danger <span id="fr_754"></span>[5](#fn_749.md).\] One whose
thoughts are (all) about enjoyments, who prospers by injuring (others),
who repents of generosity, who is miserly, who is devoid of the
power <span id="fr_755"></span>[6](#fn_750) (of knowledge.md), who esteems
the group <span id="fr_756"></span>[7](#fn_751) (of the senses.md), who
hates his wife <span id="fr_757"></span>[8](#fn_752.md)--these seven,
different (from those previously mentioned), are the seven forms of
cruelty. Knowledge, truth, self-restraint, sacred learning, freedom from
animosity (towards living beings), modesty <span
id="fr_758"></span>[9](#fn_753.md), endurance <span
id="fr_759"></span>[10](#fn_754.md), freedom from censoriousness,
sacrifice, gift, courage} <span id="fr_760"></span>[11](#fn_755.md),
quiescence <span id="fr_761"></span>[12](#fn_756.md),these are the twelve
great observances <span id="fr_762"></span>[13](#fn_757.md) of a
Brâhma*n*a. Whoever is not devoid of these twelve can govern this whole
world, and those who are

<span id="page_168">p. 168</span>

possessed of three, two, or even one (of these) become, in (due) course,
distinguished (for knowledge) and identified with the Brahman <span
id="fr_763"></span>[1](#fn_758.md). \[Self-restraint, abandonment <span
id="fr_764"></span>[2](#fn_759.md), and freedom from heedlessness--on these
depends immortality. And the talented Brâhma*n*as say that truth is
chief over them.\] Self-restraint has eighteen defects; if (any one of
them is) committed, it is an obstacle (to self-restraint), They are thus
stated. 'Untruthfulness, backbiting, thirst <span
id="fr_765"></span>[3](#fn_760), antipathy (to all beings.md),
darkness <span id="fr_766"></span>[4](#fn_761.md), repining <span
id="fr_767"></span>[5](#fn_762.md), hatred <span
id="fr_768"></span>[6](#fn_763.md) of people, haughtiness, quarrelsomeness,
injuring living creatures, reviling others, garrulity, vexation <span
id="fr_769"></span>[7](#fn_764.md), want of endurance <span
id="fr_770"></span>[8](#fn_765.md), want of courage <span
id="fr_771"></span>[9](#fn_766.md), imperfection <span
id="fr_772"></span>[10](#fn_767.md), sinful conduct, and slaughter. That is
called self-restraint by the good, which is free from these defects.
Frenzy has eighteen defects <span id="fr_773"></span>[11](#fn_768.md); and
abandonment is of six kinds. The contraries of those which have been
laid down <span id="fr_774"></span>[12](#fn_769.md) are stated to be the
defects of frenzy. Abandonment of six kinds is excellent. Of those six,
the third is hard to achieve. With it one certainly crosses

<span id="page_169">p. 169</span>

beyond all misery without distinction <span
id="fr_775"></span>[1](#fn_770). That being achieved, (everything.md) is
accomplished <span id="fr_776"></span>[2](#fn_771). The (first is the.md)
giving away of sons and wealth to a deserving man who asks (for them);
the second is gifts at Vedic ceremonies, and gifts at ceremonies laid
down in the Sm*ri*tis <span id="fr_777"></span>[3](#fn_772.md). The
abandonment of desires, O king of kings! by means of indifference (to
worldly objects) is laid down as the third <span
id="fr_778"></span>[4](#fn_773.md). With these one should become free from
heedlessness. That freedom from heedlessness, too, has eight
characteristics, and is (a) great (merit). Truthfulness, concentration,
absorbed contemplation, reflexion <span id="fr_779"></span>[5](#fn_774.md),
and also indifference (to worldly objects), not stealing <span
id="fr_780"></span>[6](#fn_775.md), living the life of a Brahma*k*ârin, and

<span id="page_170">p. 170</span>

likewise freedom from all belongings <span
id="fr_781"></span>[1](#fn_776.md). Thus have the defects of self-restraint
been stated; one should avoid those defects. Freedom from (those)
defects is freedom from heedlessness; and that, too, is deemed to have
eight characteristics <span id="fr_782"></span>[2](#fn_777.md). Let truth
be your (very) self, O king of kings! On truth all the worlds rest <span
id="fr_783"></span>[3](#fn_778.md). Truth is said to be their main
(principle). Immortality, depends on truth <span
id="fr_784"></span>[4](#fn_779). Getting rid of (these.md) defects, one
should practise the observance of penance. This is the conduct
prescribed by the Creator. Truth is the solemn vow of the good. The pure
penance, which is free from these defects, and possessed of these
characteristics, becomes developed, and well developed <span
id="fr_785"></span>[5](#fn_780.md). I will state to you, in brief, O king
of kings! what you ask of me. This (observance) <span
id="fr_786"></span>[6](#fn_781.md) is destructive of sin, and pure, and
releases (one) from birth and death and old age <span
id="fr_787"></span>[7](#fn_782.md). If one is free from the five senses,
and also from the mind <span id="fr_788"></span>[8](#fn_783.md), O
descendant of Bharata! also from (thoughts regarding) the past and the
future <span id="fr_789"></span>[9](#fn_784.md), one becomes happy.

Dh*ri*tarâsh*t*ra said:

Some people make great boasts in consequence of (their knowing) the
Vedas with the Âkhyânas as

<span id="page_171">p. 171</span>

the fifth <span id="fr_790"></span>[1](#fn_785.md); others, likewise, are
(masters) of four Vedas; others, too, of three Vedas; others are
(masters) of two Vedas, and of one Veda; and others of no Veda <span
id="fr_791"></span>[2](#fn_786.md). Tell me which of these is the greatest,
whom I may know (to be) a Brâhma*n*a.

Sanatsu*g*âta said:

Through ignorance of the one Veda <span
id="fr_792"></span>[3](#fn_787.md)--the one truth--O king of kings!
numerous Vedas came into existence. Some <span
id="fr_793"></span>[4](#fn_788.md) only adhere to the truth. The fancies of
those who have fallen away from the truth are abortive, and through
ignorance of the truth, ceremonies become amplified <span
id="fr_794"></span>[5](#fn_789.md). One should under stand a Brâhma*n*a,
who (merely) reads much, to be a man of many words <span
id="fr_795"></span>[6](#fn_790). Know him only to be the (true.md)
Brâhma*n*a, who swerves not from the truth <span
id="fr_796"></span>[7](#fn_791.md). O you who are the highest among
men <span id="fr_797"></span>[8](#fn_792.md)! the *Kh*andas, indeed, refer
of themselves <span id="fr_798"></span>[9](#fn_793.md) to it. Therefore,

<span id="page_172">p. 172</span>

studying them, the learned persons who understand the *Kh*andas, attain
to the Veda, not that which is to be known <span
id="fr_799"></span>[1](#fn_794.md). Among the Vedas, there is none which
understands <span id="fr_800"></span>[2](#fn_795.md). By the
unintelligent <span id="fr_801"></span>[3](#fn_796.md), one understands not
the Veda, nor the object of knowledge <span
id="fr_802"></span>[4](#fn_797.md). He who knows the Veda knows the object
of knowledge. He who knows the object of knowledge <span
id="fr_803"></span>[5](#fn_798.md) knows not the truth. He who understands
the Vedas understands also the object of knowledge; but that <span
id="fr_804"></span>[6](#fn_799.md) is not understood by the Vedas or by
those who understand the Vedas. Still the Brâhma*n*as who understand the
Vedas, understand the Veda by means of the Vedas <span
id="fr_805"></span>[7](#fn_800.md). As the branch of a tree with regard to
the part of a portion of the glorious <span
id="fr_806"></span>[8](#fn_801.md) one, so, they declare, are the Vedas
with

<span id="page_173">p. 173</span>

regard to the subject of understanding the supreme self. I understand
him to be a Brâhma*n*a who is ingenious, and explains <span
id="fr_807"></span>[1](#fn_802) (Vedic texts.md). He who apprehends (those
texts) thus <span id="fr_808"></span>[2](#fn_803.md), does verily know that
supreme (principle). . One should not go in search of it among (things)
antagonistic <span id="fr_809"></span>[3](#fn_804.md) to it at all. Not
looking (for him there) one sees that Lord by means of the Veda <span
id="fr_810"></span>[4](#fn_805.md). Remaining quiet, one should practise
devotion, and should not even form a wish in the mind <span
id="fr_811"></span>[5](#fn_806.md). To him, the Brahman presents <span
id="fr_812"></span>[6](#fn_807.md) itself, and directly afterwards he
attains to the perfect <span id="fr_813"></span>[7](#fn_808) (one.md). By
taciturnity <span id="fr_814"></span>[8](#fn_809.md), verily, does one
become a sage; (one does) not (become) a sage by dwelling in a
forest <span id="fr_815"></span>[9](#fn_810.md). And he is called the
highest sage, who understands that indestructible (principle). One is
called an analyser <span id="fr_816"></span>[10](#fn_811) (also.md) in
consequence of

<span id="page_174">p. 174</span>

analysing all objects. The analysis (is) from that as the root; and as
he makes (such an) analysis, hence is he so (called). The man who sees
the worlds directly sees everything <span
id="fr_817"></span>[1](sbe0825.htm#fn_812.md). A Brâhma*n*a, verily,
adhering to the truth, understands it, and becomes omniscient. I say to
you, O learned person! that adhering to knowledge and the rest <span
id="fr_818"></span>[2](sbe0825.htm#fn_813.md) in this way, one sees the
Brahman, O Kshatriya! by means of a course (of study) in the Vedas <span
id="fr_819"></span>[3](sbe0825.htm#fn_814.md).

