*S*a<u>n</u>kara.

<span id="fn_739"></span>[166:3](sbe0824.htm#fr_744.md) I. e. lust.

<span id="fn_740"></span>[166:4](sbe0824.htm#fr_745.md) Want of
discrimination between right and wrong.

<span id="fn_741"></span>[166:5](sbe0824.htm#fr_746.md) Desire to taste
worldly objects.

<span id="fn_742"></span>[166:6](sbe0824.htm#fr_747.md) For the loss of
anything desired.

<span id="fn_743"></span>[166:7](sbe0824.htm#fr_748.md) Desire to enjoy
worldly objects. The difference between this and craving, according to
*S*a<u>n</u>kara, appears to be between merely tasting and continual
enjoyment. According to Nîlaka*nth*a, the former is a desire which is
never contented; the latter is merely a general liking.

<span id="fn_744"></span>[166:8](sbe0824.htm#fr_749.md) Impatience of other
people's prosperity; censoriousness being the pointing out of flaws in
other people's merits; and reviling being an ignoring of the merits and
merely abusing.

<span id="fn_745"></span>[167:1](sbe0824.htm#fr_750.md) Scil. for attaining
to the Brahman.

<span id="fn_746"></span>[167:2](sbe0824.htm#fr_751.md) Some weak point by
which they may attack a man.

<span id="fn_747"></span>[167:3](sbe0824.htm#fr_752.md) Fickle in
friendship, &c.

<span id="fn_748"></span>[167:4](sbe0824.htm#fr_753.md) Such as a wife, &c.

<span id="fn_749"></span>[167:5](sbe0824.htm#fr_754.md) Connected with this
or the next world, Nîlaka*nth*a. This and a stanza further on I place
within brackets, as it is not quite certain whether *S*a<u>n</u>kara's
copy had them, though they are now in some of our copies of the text
with his commentary. See Introduction.

<span id="fn_750"></span>[167:6](sbe0824.htm#fr_755.md) Cf. Mu*nd*aka, p.
319; *Kh*ândogya, p. 494.

<span id="fn_751"></span>[167:7](sbe0824.htm#fr_756.md) See note , at page
[165](#page_165.md).

<span id="fn_752"></span>[167:8](sbe0824.htm#fr_757.md) The wife having no
other protector.

<span id="fn_753"></span>[167:9](sbe0824.htm#fr_758.md) See note , at page
[162](sbe0823.htm#page_162.md).

<span id="fn_754"></span>[167:10](sbe0824.htm#fr_759.md) Of pairs of
opposites, such as heat and cold, &c.

<span id="fn_755"></span>[167:11](sbe0824.htm#fr_760.md) Restraint of
senses in presence of their objects.

<span id="fn_756"></span>[167:12](sbe0824.htm#fr_761.md) Cf. Gîtâ, pp.
[69](sbe0808.htm#page_69), [70](sbe0808.htm#page_70.md).

<span id="fn_757"></span>[167:13](sbe0824.htm#fr_762.md) Which are
serviceable in attaining the highest goal.

<span id="fn_758"></span>[168:1](sbe0824.htm#fr_763.md) The original is the
word 'taciturnity' as at [p. 162](sbe0823.htm#page_162.md) supra.

<span id="fn_759"></span>[168:2](sbe0824.htm#fr_764.md) Offering one's acts
to God (Nîlaka*nth*a), as to which cf. Gîtâ, [p.
64](sbe0807.htm#page_64). See also [p. 182](sbe0825.htm#page_182.md) infra
for this stanza.

<span id="fn_760"></span>[168:3](sbe0824.htm#fr_765.md) I. e. for objects
of sense.

<span id="fn_761"></span>[168:4](sbe0824.htm#fr_766.md) Ignorance.

<span id="fn_762"></span>[168:5](sbe0824.htm#fr_767.md) Discontent even
when one obtains much.

<span id="fn_763"></span>[168:6](sbe0824.htm#fr_768.md) This is active;
antipathy is passive only.

<span id="fn_764"></span>[168:7](sbe0824.htm#fr_769.md) Of oneself, by
brooding on evil. Cf. Taittirîya, p. 119. One copy of *S*a<u>n</u>kara's
