<span id="fn_765"></span>[168:8](sbe0824.htm#fr_770.md) Of pairs of
opposites.

<span id="fn_766"></span>[168:9](sbe0824.htm#fr_771.md) Restraint of senses
in presence of their objects.

<span id="fn_767"></span>[168:10](sbe0824.htm#fr_772.md) I. e. of piety,
knowledge, and indifference to worldly objects.

<span id="fn_768"></span>[168:11](sbe0824.htm#fr_773.md) I. e. qualities
which destroy it.

<span id="fn_769"></span>[168:12](sbe0824.htm#fr_774.md) Scil. as defects
of self-restraint, viz. untruthfulness, &c.

<span id="fn_770"></span>[169:1](sbe0824.htm#fr_775.md) Scil. any
distinction as to physical, mental, or that which is caused by
superhuman agency.

<span id="fn_771"></span>[169:2](sbe0824.htm#fr_776.md) Literally, 'all is
conquered.' Everything that needs to be done is done. Cf.
Ka*th*opanishad, p. 155; Mu*nd*aka, p. 317.

<span id="fn_772"></span>[169:3](sbe0824.htm#fr_777.md) Another
interpretation of ish*t*apûrta is 'offerings to gods, and 'offerings to
the manes;' a third 'sacrifices, &c., and works of charity, such as
digging tanks and wells;' for a fourth, see *S*a<u>n</u>kara on
Mu*nd*aka, p. 291.

<span id="fn_773"></span>[169:4](sbe0824.htm#fr_778.md) Each of the three
classes mentioned contains two sub-classes, and so the six are made up.
It is not quite easy to see the two heads under the third class; but
perhaps indifference, and the consequent abandonment of desire, may be
the two intended. To indicate that, I have adopted the construction
which takes the words 'by means of indifference' with abandonment,
instead of with 'gifts at Vedic ceremonies,' &c. *S*a<u>n</u>kara seems
to understand 'giving away of wealth' with the words 'by means of
indifference,' and thus to constitute the second head under the third
class. But he is not quite clear.

<span id="fn_774"></span>[169:5](sbe0824.htm#fr_779.md) Concentration =
fixing the mind continuously on some object, such as the being in the
sun, &c.; contemplation is that in which one identifies oneself with the
Brahman; reflexion as to what one is, whence one comes, and so forth.

<span id="fn_775"></span>[169:6](sbe0824.htm#fr_780.md) *S*a<u>n</u>kara
says this may refer to the 'stealing' mentioned at [p.
160](sbe0823.htm#page_160.md). The life of a Brahma*k*ârin is here taken to
mean <span id="page_170">p. 170</span> continence by the commentators,
as also at Mu*nd*aka, p. 311 inter alia. See also *Kh*ândogya, p. 533.

<span id="fn_776"></span>[170:1](sbe0824.htm#fr_781.md) Son, wife, home,
&c.; as to which cf. Gîtâ, [p. 103](sbe0815.htm#page_103.md), and
N*ri*si*m*ha Tâpinî, p. 198, commentary.

<span id="fn_777"></span>[170:2](sbe0824.htm#fr_782.md) The eight mentioned
already.

<span id="fn_778"></span>[170:3](sbe0824.htm#fr_783.md) Cf. Taitt. Âra*n*.
p. 885.

<span id="fn_779"></span>[170:4](sbe0824.htm#fr_784.md) Cf. Mu*nd*aka, p.
312; *S*ânti Parvan (Moksha), chap. 199, st. 64 seq. Immortality = final
emancipation.

<span id="fn_780"></span>[170:5](sbe0824.htm#fr_785) [p. 165](#page_165.md)
supra.

<span id="fn_781"></span>[170:6](sbe0824.htm#fr_786.md) Of penance, that is
to say.

<span id="fn_782"></span>[170:7](sbe0824.htm#fr_787.md) Cf. Gîtâ, [p.
109](sbe0816.htm#page_109.md) for the collocation.

<span id="fn_783"></span>[170:8](sbe0824.htm#fr_788.md) Ka*th*opanishad, p.
151; Maitrî, p. 161. *S*a<u>n</u>kara, seems to take the five and the
senses separately; the five meaning the five classes of sensuous
objects.

<span id="fn_784"></span>[170:9](sbe0824.htm#fr_789.md) Past losses and
future gains, Nîlaka*nth*a.

<span id="fn_785"></span>[171:1](sbe0824.htm#fr_790.md) Cf., as to this,
Max Müller's Ancient Sanskrit Literature, p. 38 seq.; and *Kh*ândogya,
pp. 164, 474, 493; B*ri*hadâra*n*yaka, pp. 456, 687, 926; Maitrî, p.
171; Nrisimha Tâpinî, p. 105.

<span id="fn_786"></span>[171:2](sbe0824.htm#fr_791.md) The original is
'void of *Rik*s.' The commentators give no explanation. Does it mean
those who abandon the karma-mârga? Heretics who reject all Vedas are
scarcely likely to be referred to in this way. Nîlaka*nth*a's
interpretation of all this is very different. See his gloss.

<span id="fn_787"></span>[171:3](sbe0824.htm#fr_792.md) *S*a<u>n</u>kara
gives various interpretations of this. Perhaps the best is to take it as
meaning knowledge. 'The one knowledge--the one truth'--would then be
like the famous text--Taittirîya, p. 56--'The Brahman is truth,
knowledge,' &c.

<span id="fn_788"></span>[171:4](sbe0824.htm#fr_793.md) For this phrase cf.
Gîtâ, [p. 73](sbe0808.htm#page_73.md).

<span id="fn_789"></span>[171:5](sbe0824.htm#fr_794.md) Those who do not
understand the Brahman lose their natural power of obtaining what they
wish, and so go in for various ceremonies for various special benefits.
Cf. *Kh*ândogya, p. 541; Gîtâ, [p. 47](sbe0804.htm#page_47.md); and [p.
184](sbe0825.htm#page_184.md) infra.

<span id="fn_790"></span>[171:6](sbe0824.htm#fr_795.md) Cf.
B*ri*hadâranyaka, p. 893.

<span id="fn_791"></span>[171:7](sbe0824.htm#fr_796.md) Ibid. p. 636.

<span id="fn_792"></span>[171:8](sbe0824.htm#fr_797.md) Literally, 'highest
among bipeds,' a rather unusual expression.

<span id="fn_793"></span>[171:9](sbe0824.htm#fr_798.md) Nîlaka*nth*a says,
'The part of the Vedas which teaches the <span id="page_172">p.
172</span> knowledge of the supreme is enough by itself for its purpose;
it is not like the part about rites, &c., which rites must be performed
before they serve any useful purpose.' The *G*ñânakânda is enough by
itself for understanding the Brahman. *S*a<u>n</u>kara compares Gîtâ,
[p. 113](sbe0817.htm#page_113.md), and Ka*th*a, p. 102.

<span id="fn_794"></span>[172:1](sbe0824.htm#fr_799.md) The Veda = the
Brahman, as above, cf. *S*vetâ*s*vatara, p. 372 and commentary; that
