knowledge.

<span id="fn_795"></span>[172:2](sbe0824.htm#fr_800.md) Scil. understands
the Veda--the Brahman.

<span id="fn_796"></span>[172:3](sbe0824.htm#fr_801.md) 'The mind,' says
Nîlaka*nth*a; literally, 'that which is to be understood.'

<span id="fn_797"></span>[172:4](sbe0824.htm#fr_802.md) Because a real
knowledge of it requires a knowledge of the Brahman. As to the next
clause cf. inter alia *Kh*ândogya, p. 384; B*ri*hadâra*n*yaka, p. 450.

<span id="fn_798"></span>[172:5](sbe0824.htm#fr_803.md) This is the
converse of the last sentence, as to which cf. B*ri*hadâra*n*yaka, p.
925.

<span id="fn_799"></span>[172:6](sbe0824.htm#fr_804.md) The supreme.

<span id="fn_800"></span>[172:7](sbe0824.htm#fr_805.md) The apparent
contradiction is explained in the next sentence.

<span id="fn_801"></span>[172:8](sbe0824.htm#fr_806.md) I. e. the moon.
This refers to the well-known *s*âkhâ*k*andranyâya. As the small digit
of the moon, which cannot be perceived by itself, is pointed out as
being at the tip of a branch of a tree pointing towards the moon, so the
Vedas are of use as pointing towards the Brahman, though inaccurately
and imperfectly.

<span id="fn_802"></span>[173:1](sbe0824.htm#fr_807.md) Scil. in the manner
just indicated.

<span id="fn_803"></span>[173:2](sbe0824.htm#fr_808.md) As giving an idea
